<TITLE> 30 hurt as villagers clash with militants in Noakhali </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Noakhali, Mar 10 (bdnews24.com)  At least 30 people were injured as villagers clashed with alleged members of the banned militant outfit Hizb-ut-Tauhid in Chashirhat, Sonaimuri, Tuesday, police said. "Hizb-ut-Tauhid is carrying out organisational activities in the area," Noakhali ASP Mohammad Hasanuzzaman told bdnews24.com. These activities were being led by the banned outfit's district head Amir Moinuddin, of Porkora village in Chashirhat Union, said Hasanuzzaman. This had led to clashes with the locals on several occasions, he added. This time outraged villagers united to launch an organised attack on the militant leader and set fire to his house, as the banned group was holding a meeting there, police and witnesses said. At least 30 people were hurt in the clashes between villagers and the militants, they said. Three people were hit as police were forced to fire rubber bullets to douse the situation. The injured were taken to local medical centres. Some 25 people  Moinuddin, 12 militants and a dozen villagers including women and children  were detained, police said. Police also recovered a good number of militant leaflets, letters and books from Moinuddin's house, said Hasanuzzaman. Police patrols have been enhanced as tension was mounting in the area, he said. bdn
